"String / interpolation-at-scale benchmark (workload class G). Runs a
large interpolate+concat loop: each iteration builds a config line by
interpolating four fields (the desugarer lowers interpolation to string
concatenation), and every line is forced by a fold. Template rendering
(host-and-port string building) is a real product workload that had
only sub-50ms smoke tests before eu-2sa6.6.

NOTE ON SIZE: review C specified 50k iterations. Traversing/forcing a
lazy list of that length hits the shared O(n^2) fold/env-walk ceiling
(ROADMAP; review C class H), which runs into minutes. N is tuned to
7000 to land in the >1.5s band while still exercising interpolation and
concatenation under that traversal -- the genuine engine-comparison
surface for string work at scale."

# Interpolate four fields into one config line.
mk-line(i): "host-{i}.svc.local port={i} backend=be-{i} weight={i}"

# Force each interpolated string to WHNF via a cheap non-empty compare,
# counting the (all non-empty) lines. `s = ""` forces the concatenation
# but short-circuits on the length mismatch, so the per-line cost is the
# interpolation itself, not a full character walk.
force-count(acc, s): acc + if(s = "", 0, 1)

count-forced: range(0, 7000) map(mk-line) foldl(force-count, 0)

` { target: :bench-string-scale
    verify: ["default-expectation"] }
bench-string-scale: {
  lines: count-forced
  RESULT: if(count-forced = 7000, :PASS, :FAIL)
}
